The '''Devanga Purana''' is the ''kulapuranam'', or mythological history, of the [[Devanga]] community. It deals with the life of their legendary founder, Devala Maharshi, and his seven incarnations, goddess (Chowdeswari), rituals and customs. The Devanga community reside in all the south Indian states and also split in north Indian states. They are traditionally engaged in cotton cloth weaving and cloth business.
==Religion==

devanga main god Sri Ramalingadeswar and Sri Sowdeswari amman
<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/erikaraisriramalingasowdeswari/home|title=Erikarai Sri Ramalinga Sowdeswari Amman Jalakandapuram|website=sites.google.com}}</ref>


==Translations==
Around 1532 CE, Devanga people in [[Andhra Pradesh]] requested the [[Telugu language|Telugu]] poet [[Bhadralinga Kavi]] to write their ''kulapuranam'', which resulted in the Devanga Purana. It is written as poems in the ''dasimatra-dvipadi'' style.<ref name="world">{{cite book |last1=P |first1=Swarnalatha |title= The World of the Weaver in Northern Coromandel, C.1750-C.1850|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t5XlI91kP3YC&pg=PA41 |year=2005 |publisher=Orient Longman Private Limited |location=Hyderabad |isbn=978-8-12502-868-0 |page=41}}</ref>

Devanga Purana was  originally written in [[Sanskrit]] included in [[Brahmanda Purana]]; it has been translated into [[Telugu language|Telugu]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]] and [[Kannada]]. The first copy was printed in Kannada named "Badarayana".{{cn|date=January 2017}}

