{{more footnotes|date=February 2012}}
'''Harichand Thakur''', sometimes known as ''Sri Sri Harichand Thakur'', (ca. 1812-1878) worked among the [[Untouchability|untouchable]] people of [[Bengal Presidency]], who considered him to be a god.

== Life ==
Harichand Thakur is variously said to have been born in 1811<ref name="robb">{{cite book |title=A History of India |first=Peter |last=Robb |edition=2nd, revised |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |year=2011 |isbn=978-0-23034-549-2 |page=255 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GQ-2VH1LO_EC&pg=PT255}}</ref> and 1812.<ref name="sarkar">{{cite book |title=Between History and Histories: The Making of Silences and Commemorations |editor1-first=Gerald M. |editor1-last=Sider |editor2-first=Gavin A. |editor2-last=Smith |publisher=University of Toronto Press |year=1997 |isbn=978-0-80207-883-4 |chapter=Renaissance and Kaliyuga: Time, Myth, and History in Colonial Bengal |first=Sumit |last=Sarkar |page=115 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Jje8cSPgTtQC&pg=PA115}}</ref> His family were peasant farmers of the [[Namasudra]] community and he was born in the [[Gopalganj District, Bangladesh|Gopalganj area]] of what was then Bengal Presidency (now a part of Bangladesh).<ref name="bandyopadhyay">{{cite book |title=Caste, Culture and Hegemony: Social Dominance in Colonial Bengal |first=Sekhar |last=Bandyopadhyay |publisher=SAGE |year=2004 |isbn=978-0-76199-849-5 |page=96 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=z2SVIflbyHQC&pg=PA96}}</ref> Named Harichand Bairagi at birth, he moved to [[Orakandi]], [[Faridpur District]].{{cn|date=April 2018}}

At a very early age, Thakur accepted the path of religious reformation for giving service to and uplifting the untouchable people of Bengal. He experienced ''atmadarshan'' (self-realisation) and preached his ideologies and religious philosophy in twelve commandments and asked his followers to pursue his works.{{cn|date=July 2017}}

Thakur, whose family were [[Vaishnavite]] Hindus,<ref name="bandyopadhyay"/> founded a sect of Vaishnavite Hinduism called [[Matua Mahasangha|Matua]]. This was adopted by members of the Namasudra community, who were then also known by the pejorative name of [[Chandala]]s and considered to be untouchable.<ref name="sarkar"/><ref>{{cite book |title=The Politics of Caste in West Bengal |editor1-first=Uday |editor1-last=Chandra |editor2-first=Geir |editor2-last=Heierstad |editor3-first=Kenneth Bo |editor3-last=Nielsen |publisher=Routledge |year=2015 |isbn=978-1-31741-477-3 |chapter=Building Up the Harichand-Guruchand Movement: The Politics of the Matua Mahansgha |first=Praskanva |last=Sinharay |page=152 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7qXbCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA152}}</ref> The sect was opposed to Brahmanical Hinduism and, according to Sipra Mukherjee "[inspired] the community towards education and social upliftment". It has subsequently attracted adherents from other caste communities that were marginalised by the upper castes, including the [[Chamar]]s, [[Mahishya]]s, [[Mali caste|Mali]]s, and [[Teli]]s.<ref name="mukherjee">{{cite book |first=Sipra |last=Mukherjee |chapter=Creating Their Own Gods: Literature from the Margins of Bengal |title=Dalit Literatures in India |editor1-first=Joshil K. |editor1-last=Abraham |editor2-first=Judith |editor2-last=Misrahi-Barak |publisher=Routledge |year=2015 |isbn=978-1-31740-880-2 |pages=132, 140 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Ph4-CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA132}}</ref>

Thakur's followers consider him as God (hence calling him ''Thakur'') Harichand and as an [[avatar]] (incarnation) of [[Vishnu]] or [[Krishna]]. Thus, he became known as ''Sri Sri Harichand Thakur''.{{cn|date=July 2017}} However, adherents of mainstream Hinduism do not accept this, despite often assimilating offshoots of their faith, because, according to the [[Dalit|Dalit activist]] [[Debendralal Biswas Thakur]], to do so in this instance would be to undermine the basis of their religion.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Politics of Caste in West Bengal |editor1-first=Uday |editor1-last=Chandra |editor2-first=Geir |editor2-last=Heierstad |editor3-first=Kenneth Bo |editor3-last=Nielsen |publisher=Routledge |year=2015 |isbn=978-1-31741-477-3 |chapter=Building Up the Harichand-Guruchand Movement: The Politics of the Matua Mahansgha |first=Praskanva |last=Sinharay |page=159 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7qXbCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA159}}</ref>

Thakur was married to Jagat Mata Shanti Mata and they had two sons. He died at Orakandi in 1878.

== Legacy ==
After his death, one of his sons, Guruchand Thakur (b. 1846), worked with C. S. Mead in a campaign to have the Chandala people [[sanskritisation|recategorised as Namasudra]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Namasudra Movements In Bengal (1872-1947)|first=Ratan Kumar |last=Biswas|publisher=Progressive Book Forum |year=2010 |isbn=978-81-88006-19-9 |page=158-160}}</ref> According to historian [[Sekhar Bandyopadhyay]], it was under the leadership of Guruchand that the Matua sect "achieved its doctrinal cohesion and organisational push, as it came to be associated with the Namasudra social protest movement started in 1872".<ref name="bandyopadhyay"/>

A considerable body of [[Dalit literature]] that mixes religious and secular themes has emerged around Thakur and Matua. This includes biographies, promotions of the teachings and interpretations of the relationship to later events, such as the thoughts of [[B. R. Ambedkar]] and comparisons with the situation of black people in the US.<ref name="mukherjee"/>

