[[Category:Theosophy]]

'''Yosef Eliyahu Deutch''' was a [[Jerusalem]] [[rabbi]] and philanthropist. He was born in Jerusalem in 1922 and died there in 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chasdei.org/history_h.php |title=הסטוריה - חסדי יוסף - מסורת של נתינה |publisher=Chasdei.org |date= |accessdate=2014-08-22}}</ref> He was the son of [[Lelov]] hasid and Jerusalemite Rabbi [[Matisyahu Deutch]], author of "Divrei Matisyahu".<ref>{{cite web|author=אשכנזי, מתתיהו בן יהודה ליב |url=http://www.hebrewbooks.org/40563 |title=Sefer Detail: דברי מתתיהו ובית דוד - אשכנזי, מתתיהו בן יהודה ליב |publisher=Hebrewbooks.org |date= |accessdate=2014-08-22}}</ref>
Deutch headed the "Anshei Mamad" Yeshiva for Halacha and Kabbala in Jerusalem which is currently headed by his son Rabbi Shneur Deutch. Deutch's soup kitchens and other charitable institutions named "Chasdei Yosef" are headed by his son Rabbi Moshe Deutch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chasdei.org |title=Chasdei Yosef - A Tradition of giving |publisher=Chasdei.org |date= |accessdate=2014-08-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jdn.co.il/news/8743 |title=מירון של ירושלים • המונים עלו להילולת שמעון הצדיק - JDN - חדשות |publisher=JDN |date=2013-08-13 |accessdate=2014-08-22}}</ref> His eldest son Rabbi [[Chaim Shalom Deutch]] is a prominent [[Chabad]] hasid.
